[src:hyper-rust/http-2] The standardization effort was supported by the Chrome, Opera, Firefox, Internet Explorer 11, Safari, Amazon Silk, and Edge browsers.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] Most major browsers had added HTTP/2 support by the end of 2015.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] About 97% of web browsers used have the capability (and 100% of "tracked desktop" web browsers).
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] As of July 2023, 36% (after topping out at just over 50%) of the top 10 million websites support HTTP/2.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] Its successor is HTTP/3, a major revision that builds on the concepts established by HTTP/2.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] The changes do not require any changes to how existing web applications work, but new applications can take advantage of new features for increased speed.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] HTTP/2 leaves all of HTTP/1.1's high-level semantics, such as methods, status codes, header fields, and URIs, the same.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] What is new is how the data is framed and transported between the client and the server.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] Websites that are efficient minimize the number of requests required to render an entire page by minifying (reducing the amount of code and packing smaller pieces of code into bundles, without reducing its ability to function) resources such as images and scripts.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] However, minification is not necessarily convenient nor efficient and may still require separate HTTP connections to get the page and the minified resources.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] HTTP/2 allows the server to "push" content, that is, to respond with data for more queries than the client requested.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] This allows the server to supply data it knows a web browser will need to render a web page, without waiting for the browser to examine the first response, and without the overhead of an additional request cycle.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] Additional performance improvements in the first draft of HTTP/2 (which was a copy of SPDY) come from multiplexing of requests and responses to avoid some of the head-of-line blocking problem in HTTP 1 (even when HTTP pipelining is used), header compression, and prioritization of requests.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] However, as HTTP/2 runs on top of a single TCP connection, there is still potential for head-of-line blocking to occur if TCP packets are lost or delayed in transmission.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] HTTP/2 no longer supports HTTP/1.1's chunked transfer encoding mechanism, as it provides its own, more efficient mechanisms for data streaming.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] SPDY (pronounced like "speedy") was a previous HTTP-replacement protocol developed by a research project spearheaded by Google.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] Primarily focused on reducing latency, SPDY uses the same TCP pipe but different protocols to accomplish this reduction.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] The basic changes made to HTTP/1.1 to create SPDY included "true request pipelining without FIFO restrictions, message framing mechanism to simplify client and server development, mandatory compression (including headers), priority scheduling, and even bi-directional communication".
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] The HTTP Working Group considered Google's SPDY protocol, Microsoft's HTTP Speed+Mobility proposal (SPDY based), and Network-Friendly HTTP Upgrade.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] In July 2012, Facebook provided feedback on each of the proposals and recommended HTTP/2 be based on SPDY.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] The initial draft of HTTP/2 was published in November 2012 and was based on a straight copy of SPDY.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] The biggest difference between HTTP/1.1 and SPDY was that each user action in SPDY is given a "stream ID", meaning there is a single TCP channel connecting the user to the server.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] SPDY split requests into either control or data, using a "simple to parse binary protocol with two types of frames".
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] SPDY showed evident improvement over HTTP, with a new page load speedup ranging from 11% to 47%.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] The development of HTTP/2 used SPDY as a jumping-off point.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] Among the many detailed differences between the protocols, the most notable is that HTTP/2 uses a fixed Huffman code-based header compression algorithm, instead of SPDY's dynamic stream-based compression.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] This helps to reduce the potential for compression oracle attacks on the protocol, such as the CRIME attack.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] On February 9, 2015, Google announced plans to remove support for SPDY in Chrome in favor of support for HTTP/2.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] This took effect starting with Chrome 51.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] HTTP/2 is defined for both HTTP URIs (without TLS encryption, a configuration which is abbreviated as **h2c**) and HTTPS URIs (over TLS using ALPN extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required, a configuration which is abbreviated as **h2**).
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] Although the standard itself does not require usage of encryption, all major client implementations (Chrome, Edge, Firefox, Internet Explorer, Opera, Safari) have stated they will only support HTTP/2 over TLS, which makes encryption de facto mandatory.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] The FreeBSD and Varnish developer Poul-Henning Kamp asserts that the standard was prepared on an unrealistically short schedule, ruling out any basis for the new HTTP/2 other than the SPDY protocol and resulting in other missed opportunities for improvement.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] Kamp criticizes the protocol itself for being inconsistent and having needless, overwhelming complexity.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] He also states that the protocol violates the protocol layering principle, for example by duplicating flow control that belongs in the transport layer (TCP).
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] He also suggested that the new protocol should have removed HTTP Cookies, introducing a breaking change.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] Initially, some members of the Working Group tried to introduce an encryption requirement in the protocol.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] Critics stated that encryption has non-negligible computing costs and that many HTTP applications actually have no need for encryption and their providers have no desire to spend additional resources on it.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] Encryption proponents have stated that this encryption overhead is negligible in practice.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] Poul-Henning Kamp has criticized the IETF for hastily standardizing Google's SPDY prototype as HTTP/2 due to political considerations.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] In the end the Working Group did not reach consensus over the mandatory encryption, although most client implementations require it, which makes encryption a *de facto* requirement.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] The HTTP/2 protocol also faced criticism for not supporting opportunistic encryption, a measure against passive monitoring similar to the STARTTLS mechanism that has long been available in other Internet protocols like SMTP.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] Critics have stated that the HTTP/2 proposal goes in violation of IETF's own RFC 7258 "Pervasive Monitoring Is an Attack", which also has a status of Best Current Practice 188.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] RFC7258/BCP188 mandates that pervasive monitoring be considered as an attack, and protocols designed by IETF should take steps to protect against passive monitoring (for example, through the use of opportunistic encryption).
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] A number of specifications for opportunistic encryption of HTTP/2 have been provided, of which draft-nottingham-http2-encryption was adopted as an official work item of the working group, leading to the publication of RFC 8164 in May 2017.
[src:hyper-rust/http-2] This head-of-line blocking in HTTP/2 is now widely regarded as a design flaw, and much of the effort behind QUIC and HTTP/3 has been devoted to reduce head-of-line blocking issues.
[src:hyper-rust/latest-hyper] hyper is a **fast** and **correct** HTTP implementation written in and for Rust.
[src:hyper-rust/latest-hyper] hyper is a lower-level HTTP library, meant to be a building block for libraries and applications.
[src:hyper-rust/latest-hyper] If looking for just a convenient HTTP client, consider the reqwest crate.
[src:hyper-rust/latest-hyper] Futures returned by hyper are cancel safe: dropping a future before it completes is the supported way to cancel the operation.
[src:hyper-rust/latest-hyper] See the documentation on individual futures — for example `SendRequest::send_request` in `client::conn::http1` and `client::conn::http2` — for the protocol- specific behavior on cancellation.
[src:hyper-rust/latest-hyper] hyper uses a set of feature flags to reduce the amount of compiled code.
[src:hyper-rust/latest-hyper] It is possible to just enable certain features over others.
[src:hyper-rust/latest-hyper] By default, hyper does not enable any features but allows one to enable a subset for their use case.
[src:hyper-rust/latest-hyper] Below is a list of the available feature flags.
[src:hyper-rust/latest-hyper] You may also notice above each function, struct and trait there is listed one or more feature flags that are required for that item to be used.
[src:hyper-rust/latest-hyper] If you are new to hyper it is possible to enable the `full` feature flag which will enable all public APIs.
[src:hyper-rust/latest-hyper] Beware though that this will pull in many extra dependencies that you may not need.
[src:hyper-rust/latest-hyper] hyper includes a set of unstable optional features that can be enabled through the use of a feature flag and a configuration flag.
[src:hyper-rust/latest-hyper] It’s worth talking a bit about the stability of hyper. hyper’s API follows SemVer.
[src:hyper-rust/latest-hyper] Breaking changes will only be introduced in major versions, if ever.
[src:hyper-rust/latest-hyper] New additions to the API, such as new types, methods, or traits will only be added in minor versions.
[src:hyper-rust/latest-hyper] Some parts of hyper are documented as NOT being part of the stable API.
[src:hyper-rust/latest-hyper] The following is a brief list, you can read more about each one in the relevant part of the documentation.
[src:hyper-rust/latest-hyper] Streaming bodies for Requests and Responses.
[src:hyper-rust/latest-hyper] Represents errors that can occur handling HTTP streams.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] A **network socket** is a software structure within a network node of a computer network that serves as an endpoint for sending and receiving data across the network.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] The structure and properties of a socket are defined by an application programming interface (API) for the networking architecture.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] Sockets are created only during the lifetime of a process of an application running in the node.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] Because of the standardization of the TCP/IP protocols in the development of the Internet, the term *network socket* is most commonly used in the context of the Internet protocol suite, and is therefore often also referred to as **Internet socket**.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] In this context, a socket is externally identified to other hosts by its **socket address**, which is the triad of transport protocol, IP address, and port number.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] The term *socket* is also used for the software endpoint of node-internal inter-process communication (IPC), which often uses the same API as a network socket.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] The use of the term *socket* in software is analogous to the function of an electrical female connector, a device in hardware for communication between nodes interconnected with an electrical cable.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] Similarly, the term *port* refers to external physical endpoints at a node or device.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] The application programming interface (API) for the network protocol stack creates a handle for each socket created by an application, commonly referred to as a *socket descriptor*.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] In Unix-like operating systems, this descriptor is a type of file descriptor.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] It is stored by the application process for use with every read and write operation on the communication channel.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] At the time of creation with the API, a network socket is bound to the combination of a type of network protocol to be used for transmissions, a network address of the host, and a port number.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] Ports are numbered resources that represent another type of software structure of the node.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] They are used as service types, and, once created by a process, serve as an externally (from the network) addressable location component, so that other hosts may establish connections.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] Network sockets may be dedicated for persistent connections for communication between two nodes, or they may participate in connectionless and multicast communications.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] In practice, due to the proliferation of the TCP/IP protocols in use on the Internet, the term *network socket* usually refers to use with the Internet Protocol (IP).
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] It is therefore often also called **Internet socket**.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] An application can communicate with a remote process by exchanging data with TCP/IP by knowing the combination of protocol type, IP address, and port number.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] This combination is often known as a *socket address*.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] It is the network-facing access handle to the network socket.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] The remote process establishes a network socket in its own instance of the protocol stack and uses the networking API to connect to the application, presenting its own socket address for use by the application.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] A protocol stack, usually provided by the operating system (rather than as a separate library, for instance), is a set of services that allows processes to communicate over a network using the protocols that the stack implements.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] The operating system forwards the payload of incoming IP packets to the corresponding application by extracting the socket address information from the IP and transport protocol headers and stripping the headers from the application data.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] The application programming interface (API) that programs use to communicate with the protocol stack, using network sockets, is called a **socket API**.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] Development of application programs that utilize this API is called *socket programming* or *network programming*.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] Internet socket APIs are usually based on the Berkeley sockets standard.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] In the Berkeley sockets standard, sockets are a form of file descriptor, due to the Unix philosophy that "everything is a file", and the analogies between sockets and files.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] Both have functions to read, write, open, and close.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] In practice, the differences strain the analogy, and different interfaces (send and receive) are used on a socket.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] In inter-process communication, each end generally has its own socket.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] In the standard Internet protocols TCP and UDP, a socket address is the combination of an IP address and a port number, much like one end of a telephone connection is the combination of a phone number and a particular extension.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] Sockets need not have a source address, for example, for only sending data, but if a program *binds* a socket to a source address, the socket can be used to receive data sent to that address.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] Based on this address, Internet sockets deliver incoming data packets to the appropriate application process.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] The distinctions between a socket (internal representation), socket descriptor (abstract identifier), and socket address (public address) are subtle, and these are not always distinguished in everyday usage.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] Further, specific definitions of a *socket* differ between authors.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] In IETF Request for Comments, Internet Standards, in many textbooks, as well as in this article, the term *socket* refers to an entity that is uniquely identified by the socket number.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] In other textbooks, the term *socket* refers to a local socket address, i.e., a "combination of an IP address and a port number".
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] In the original definition of *socket* given in RFC 147, as it was related to the ARPA network in 1971, *"the socket is specified as a 32-bit number with even sockets identifying receiving sockets and odd sockets identifying sending sockets."* Today, however, socket communications are bidirectional.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] Within the operating system and the application that created a socket, a socket is referred to by a unique integer value called a *socket descriptor*.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] On Unix-like operating systems and Microsoft Windows, the command-line tools netstat or ss are used to list established sockets and related information.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] This example in Java, modeled according to the Berkeley socket interface, sends the string "Hello, world!" via TCP to port `80` of the host with address `203.0.113.0`.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] Each packet sent or received on a datagram socket is individually addressed and routed.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] Order and reliability are not guaranteed with datagram sockets, so multiple packets sent from one machine or process to another may arrive in any order or might not arrive at all.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] In order to receive broadcast packets, a datagram socket should not be bound to a specific address, though in some implementations, broadcast packets may also be received when a datagram socket is bound to a specific address.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] and unique flow of error-free data without record boundaries, with well-defined mechanisms for creating and destroying connections and reporting errors.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] On the Internet, stream sockets are typically implemented using TCP so that applications can run across any network using TCP/IP protocol.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] Allow direct sending and receiving of IP packets without any protocol-specific transport layer formatting.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] according to the chosen transport layer protocol (e.g.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] When reading from a raw socket, the headers are usually included.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] When transmitting packets from a raw socket, the automatic addition of a header is optional.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] (APIs), for example, those based on Berkeley sockets, support raw sockets.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] interface, but three years later, Microsoft limited Winsock's raw socket support because of security concerns.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] Other socket types are implemented over other transport protocols, such as Systems Network Architecture and Unix domain sockets for internal inter-process communication.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] Computer processes that provide application services are referred to as servers, and create sockets on startup that are in the *listening state*.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] These sockets are waiting for initiatives from client programs.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] A TCP server may serve several clients concurrently by creating a unique dedicated socket for each client connection in a new child process or processing thread for each client.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] These are in the *established state* when a socket-to-socket virtual connection or virtual circuit (VC), also known as a TCP session, is established with the remote socket, providing a duplex byte stream.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] A server may create several concurrently established TCP sockets with the same local port number and local IP address, each mapped to its own server-child process, serving its own client process.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] They are treated as different sockets by the operating system since the remote socket address (the client IP address or port number) is different; i.e., since they have different socket pair tuples.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] UDP sockets do not have an *established state*, because the protocol is connectionless.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] A UDP server process handles incoming datagrams from all remote clients sequentially through the same socket.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] UDP sockets are not identified by the remote address, but only by the local address, although each message has an associated remote address that can be retrieved from each datagram with the networking application programming interface (API).
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] Local and remote sockets communicating over TCP are called **socket pairs**.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] Each socket pair is described by a unique 4-tuple consisting of source and destination IP addresses and port numbers, i.e. of local and remote socket addresses.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] As discussed above, in the TCP case, a socket pair is associated on each end of the connection with a unique 4-tuple.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] The term *socket* dates to the publication of RFC 147 in 1971, when it was used in the ARPANET.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] Most modern implementations of sockets are based on Berkeley sockets (1983), and other stacks such as Winsock (1991).
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] The Berkeley sockets API in the Berkeley Software Distribution (BSD) originated with the 4.2BSD Unix operating system as an API.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] Only in 1989, however, could UC Berkeley release versions of its operating system and networking library free from the licensing constraints of AT&T's copyright-protected Unix.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] 1987, AT&T introduced the STREAMS-based Transport Layer Interface (TLI) in UNIX System V Release 3 (SVR3). and continued into Release 4 (SVR4).
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] Other early implementations were written for TOPS-20, MVS, VM, IBM-DOS (PCIP).
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] The socket is primarily a concept used in the transport layer of the Internet protocol suite or session layer of the OSI model.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] Networking equipment such as routers, which operate at the internet layer, and switches, which operate at the link layer, do not require implementations of the transport layer.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] However, stateful network firewalls, network address translators, and proxy servers keep track of active socket pairs.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] In multilayer switches and quality of service (QoS) support in routers, packet flows may be identified by extracting information about the socket pairs.
[src:hyper-rust/network-socket] Raw sockets are typically available in network equipment and are used for routing protocols such as IGRP and OSPF, and for Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP).
[src:hyper-rust/persistent-connection] Under HTTP 1.0, connections should always be **closed** by the server after sending the response.
[src:hyper-rust/persistent-connection] Since at least late 1995, developers of popular products (browsers, web servers, etc.) using HTTP/1.0, started to add an unofficial extension (to the protocol) named "keep-alive" in order to allow the reuse of a connection for multiple requests/responses.
[src:hyper-rust/persistent-connection] When the server receives this request and generates a response, if it supports keep-alive then it also adds the same above header to the response.
[src:hyper-rust/persistent-connection] Following this, the connection is not dropped, but is instead kept open.
[src:hyper-rust/persistent-connection] When the client sends another request, it uses the same connection.
[src:hyper-rust/persistent-connection] After that the connection is closed following specified rules.
[src:hyper-rust/persistent-connection] Since 1997, the various versions of HTTP/1.1 specifications acknowledged the usage of this unofficial extension and included a few caveats regarding the interoperability between HTTP/1.0 (keep-alive) and HTTP/1.1 clients / servers.
[src:hyper-rust/persistent-connection] In HTTP 1.1, all connections are considered persistent unless declared otherwise.
[src:hyper-rust/persistent-connection] The HTTP **persistent connections** do not use separate keepalive messages, they just allow multiple requests to use a single connection.
[src:hyper-rust/persistent-connection] However, the default connection timeout of Apache httpd 1.3 and 2.0 is as little as 15 seconds and just 5 seconds for Apache httpd 2.2 and above.
[src:hyper-rust/persistent-connection] The advantage of a short timeout is the ability to deliver multiple components of a web page quickly while not consuming resources to run multiple server processes or threads for too long.
[src:hyper-rust/persistent-connection] Keepalive makes it difficult for the client to determine where one response ends and the next response begins, particularly during pipelined HTTP operation.
[src:hyper-rust/persistent-connection] This is a serious problem when `Content-Length` cannot be used due to streaming.
[src:hyper-rust/persistent-connection] To solve this problem, HTTP 1.1 introduced a chunked transfer coding that defines a `last-chunk` bit.
[src:hyper-rust/persistent-connection] The `last-chunk` bit is set at the end of each response so that the client knows where the next response begins.
[src:hyper-rust/persistent-connection] According to RFC 7230, section 6.4, "a client ought to limit the number of simultaneous open connections that it maintains to a given server".
[src:hyper-rust/persistent-connection] The previous version of the HTTP/1.1 specification stated specific maximum values but in the words of RFC 7230 "this was found to be impractical for many applications... instead... be conservative when opening multiple connections".
[src:hyper-rust/persistent-connection] These guidelines are intended to improve HTTP response times and avoid congestion.
[src:hyper-rust/persistent-connection] If HTTP pipelining is correctly implemented, there is no performance benefit to be gained from additional connections, while additional connections may cause issues with congestion.
[src:hyper-rust/persistent-connection] If the client does not close the connection when all of the data it needs has been received, the resources needed to keep the connection open on the server will be unavailable for other clients.
[src:hyper-rust/persistent-connection] This affects both server's availability and the availability of resources on the server, with the degree of impact depending on the server's architecture and configuration.
[src:hyper-rust/persistent-connection] Also a race condition can occur where the client sends a request to the server at the same time that the server closes the TCP connection.
[src:hyper-rust/persistent-connection] A server should send a 408 Request Timeout status code to the client immediately before closing the connection.
[src:hyper-rust/persistent-connection] When a client receives the 408 status code, after having sent the request, it may open a new connection to the server and re-send the request.
[src:hyper-rust/persistent-connection] Not all clients will re-send the request, and many that do will only do so if the request has an idempotent HTTP method.
[src:hyper-rust/persistent-connection] All modern web browsers including Chrome, Edge, Firefox, Opera (since 4.0), and Safari use persistent connections.
[src:hyper-rust/persistent-connection] In Firefox, the number of simultaneous connections can be customized (per-server, per-proxy, total).
[src:hyper-rust/persistent-connection] Persistent connections time out after 115 seconds (1.92 minutes) of inactivity which is changeable via the configuration.
[src:hyper-rust/persistent-connection] Python's `requests` library contains `requests.Session()`, which establishes a persistent HTTP connection, thereby allowing the underlying TCP connection to be reused, which can result in a significant performance increase.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports multiple programming paradigms.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] It was influenced by ideas from functional programming, including immutability, higher-order functions, algebraic data types, and pattern matching.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] It also supports object-oriented programming via structs, enums, traits, and methods.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust enforces memory safety (i.e., that all references point to valid memory) without a conventional garbage collector; instead, memory safety errors and data races are prevented by the "borrow checker", which tracks the object lifetime of references at compile time.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Software developer Graydon Hoare created Rust in 2006 while working at Mozilla, which officially sponsored the project in 2009.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The first stable release, Rust 1.0, was published in May 2015.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The project has been sponsored by the Rust Foundation since February 2021.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust has been adopted by many software projects, especially web services and system software.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] It has been studied academically and has a growing community of developers.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust began as a personal project by Mozilla employee Graydon Hoare in 2006.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] According to *MIT Technology Review*, he started the project due to his frustration with a broken elevator in his apartment building whose software had crashed, and named the language after the group of fungi of the same name that is "over-engineered for survival".
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] During the time period between 2006 and 2009, Rust was not publicized to others at Mozilla and was written in Hoare's free time; Hoare began speaking about the language around 2009 after a small group at Mozilla became interested in the project.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Hoare cited languages from the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s as influences — including CLU, BETA, Mesa, NIL, Erlang, Newsqueak, Napier, Hermes, Sather, Alef, and Limbo.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] During the early years, the Rust compiler was written in about 38,000 lines of OCaml.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Early Rust contained several features no longer present today, including explicit object-oriented programming via an `obj` keyword and a typestates system for variable state changes, such as going from uninitialized to initialized.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Mozilla officially sponsored the Rust project in 2009.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Brendan Eich and other executives, intrigued by the possibility of using Rust for a safe web browser engine, placed engineers on the project including Patrick Walton, Niko Matsakis, Felix Klock, and Manish Goregaokar.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] A conference room taken by the project developers was dubbed "the nerd cave," with a sign placed outside the door.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] During this time period, work had shifted from the initial OCaml compiler to a self-hosting compiler (*i.e.*, written in Rust) targeting LLVM.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The ownership system was in place by 2010.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust logo was developed in 2011 based on a bicycle chainring.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust 0.1 became the first public release on January 20, 2012 for Windows, Linux, and MacOS.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The early 2010s witnessed increasing involvement from full-time engineers at Mozilla and open source volunteers outside Mozilla.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The years from 2012 to 2015 were marked by substantial changes to the Rust type system.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory management through the ownership system was gradually consolidated and expanded.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] By 2013, the garbage collector was rarely used, and was removed in favor of the ownership system.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Other features were removed in order to simplify the language, including typestates, the `pure` keyword, various specialized pointer types, and syntax support for channels.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] According to Steve Klabnik, Rust was influenced during this period by developers coming from C++ (e.g., low-level performance of features), scripting languages (e.g., Cargo and package management), and functional programming (e.g., type systems development).
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Graydon Hoare stepped down from Rust in 2013.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] After Hoare's departure, it evolved organically under a federated governance structure, with a "core team" of initially six people, and around 30-40 developers total across various other teams.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] A Request for Comments (RFC) process for new language features was added in March 2014.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The core team would grow to nine people by 2016 with over 1600 RFCs.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Dobb's Journal* in January 2014, while Rust was "widely viewed as a remarkably elegant language", adoption slowed because it radically changed from version to version.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust development at this time focused on finalizing features for version 1.0 so that it could begin promising backward compatibility.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Six years after Mozilla's sponsorship, Rust 1.0 was published and became the first stable release on May 15, 2015.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] A year later, the Rust compiler had accumulated over 1,400 contributors, and there were over 5,000 third-party libraries published on the Rust package management website Crates.io.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The development of the Servo browser engine continued in parallel with Rust, jointly funded by Mozilla and Samsung.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The teams behind the two projects worked in close collaboration; new features in Rust were tested out by the Servo team, and new features in Servo were used to give feedback back to the Rust team.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The first version of Servo was released in 2016.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The Firefox web browser shipped with Rust code as of 2016 (version 45), but components of Servo did not appear in Firefox until September 2017 (version 57) as part of the Gecko and Quantum projects.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Improvements were made to the Rust toolchain ecosystem during the years following 1.0 including Rustfmt, integrated development environment integration, and a regular compiler testing and release cycle.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's community gained a code of conduct and an IRC chat for discussion.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The earliest known adoption outside of Mozilla was by individual projects at Samsung, Facebook (now Meta Platforms), Dropbox, and Tilde, Inc., the company behind ember.js.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Engineers cited performance, lack of a garbage collector, safety, and pleasantness of working in the language as reasons for the adoption.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Amazon developers cited a finding by Portuguese researchers that Rust code used less energy compared to similar code written in Java.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] In August 2020, Mozilla laid off 250 of its 1,000 employees worldwide, as part of a corporate restructuring caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The event raised concerns about the future of Rust.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] In the following week, the Rust Core Team acknowledged the severe impact of the layoffs and announced that plans for a Rust foundation were underway.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The first goal of the foundation would be to take ownership of all trademarks and domain names and to take financial responsibility for their costs.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] On February 8, 2021, the formation of the Rust Foundation was announced by five founding companies: Amazon Web Services, Google, Huawei, Microsoft, and Mozilla.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The foundation would provide financial support for Rust developers in the form of grants and server funding.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] In a blog post published on April 6, 2021, Google announced support for Rust within the Android Open Source Project as an alternative to C/C++.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] On November 22, 2021, the Moderation Team, which was responsible for enforcing the community code of conduct, announced their resignation "in protest of the Core Team placing themselves unaccountable to anyone but themselves".
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] In May 2022, members of the Rust leadership council posted a public response to the incident.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust Foundation posted a draft for a new trademark policy on April 6, 2023, which resulted in widespread negative reactions from Rust users and contributors.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The trademark policy included rules for how the Rust logo and name could be used.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's syntax is similar to that of C and C++, although many of its features were influenced by functional programming languages such as OCaml.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Hoare has described Rust as targeted at frustrated C++ developers.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Below is a "Hello, World!" program in Rust.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The `fn` keyword denotes a function, and the `println!` macro (see § Macros) prints the message to standard output.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Statements in Rust are separated by semicolons.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Variables in Rust are defined through the `let` keyword.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The example below assigns a value to the variable with name `foo` of type `i32` and outputs its value; the type annotation `: i32` can be omitted.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Variables are immutable by default, unless the `mut` keyword is added.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The following example uses `//`, which denotes the start of a comment.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Multiple `let` expressions can define multiple variables with the same name, known as variable shadowing.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing allows transforming variables without having to name the variables differently.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing is also possible for values of different types.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] A *block expression* is delimited by curly brackets.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] An `if` conditional expression executes code based on whether the given value is `true`.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] `else` can be used for when the value evaluates to `false`, and `else if` can be used for combining multiple expressions.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] `while` can be used to repeat a block of code while a condition is met.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] For loops in Rust loop over elements of a collection.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] `for` expressions work over any iterator type.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] In the above code, `4..=10` is a value of type `Range` which implements the `Iterator` trait.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The code within the curly braces is applied to each element returned by the iterator.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Iterators can be combined with functions over iterators like `map`, `filter`, and `sum`.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] More generally, the `loop` keyword allows repeating a portion of code until a `break` occurs.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] `break` may optionally exit the loop with a value.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] In the case of nested loops, labels denoted by `'label_name` can be used to break an outer loop rather than the innermost loop.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The `match` and `if let` expressions can be used for pattern matching.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust is strongly typed and statically typed, meaning that the types of all variables must be known at compilation time.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Assigning a value of a particular type to a differently typed variable causes a compilation error.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Type inference is used to determine the type of variables if unspecified.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The type `()`, called the "unit type" in Rust, is a concrete type that has exactly one value.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] It occupies no memory (as it represents the absence of value).
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] All functions that do not have an indicated return type implicitly return `()`.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] It is similar to `void` in other C-style languages; however, `void` denotes the absence of a type and cannot have any value.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The default integer type is `i32`, and the default floating point type is `f64`.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] If the type of a literal number is not explicitly provided, it is either inferred from the context or the default type is used.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Integer types in Rust are named based on the signedness and the number of bits the type takes.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, `i32` is a signed integer that takes 32 bits of storage, whereas `u8` is unsigned and only takes 8 bits of storage.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] `isize` and `usize` take storage depending on the memory address bus width of the compilation target.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, when building for 32-bit targets, both types will take up 32 bits of space.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals are in base-10, but different radices are supported with prefixes, for example, `0b11` for binary numbers, `0o567` for octals, and `0xDB` for hexadecimals.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals default to `i32` as its type.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Suffixes such as `4u32` can be used to explicitly set the type of a literal.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Byte literals such as `b'X'` are available to represent the ASCII value (as a `u8`) of a specific character.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The Boolean type is referred to as `bool` which can take a value of either `true` or `false`.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] A `char` takes up 32 bits of space and represents a Unicode scalar value: a Unicode codepoint that is not a surrogate.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] IEEE 754 floating point numbers are supported with `f32` for single precision floats and `f64` for double precision floats.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Compound types can contain multiple values.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Tuples are fixed-size lists that can contain values whose types can be different.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Arrays are fixed-size lists whose values are of the same type.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's ownership system consists of rules that ensure memory safety without using a garbage collector.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] At compile time, each value must be attached to a variable called the *owner* of that value, and every value must have exactly one owner.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Values are moved between different owners through assignment or passing a value as a function parameter.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Values can also be *borrowed,* meaning they are temporarily passed to a different function before being returned to the owner.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Because of these ownership rules, Rust types are known as *affine types*, meaning each value may be used at most once.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] This enforces a form of software fault isolation as the owner of a value is solely responsible for its correctness and deallocation.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] When a value goes out of scope, it is *dropped* by running its destructor.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The destructor may be programmatically defined through implementing the `Drop` trait.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] This helps manage resources such as file handles, network sockets, and locks, since when objects are dropped, the resources associated with them are closed or released automatically.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Object lifetime refers to the period of time during which a reference is valid; that is, the time between the object creation and destruction.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] These *lifetimes* are implicitly associated with all Rust reference types.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] While often inferred, they can also be indicated explicitly with named lifetime parameters (often denoted `'a`, `'b`, and so on).
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] A value's lifetime in Rust is inferred from the set of locations in the source code (i.e., function, line, and column numbers) for which a variable is valid.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, a reference to a local variable has a lifetime from the expression it is declared in up until the last use of it.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The borrow checker in the Rust compiler then enforces that references are only used in the locations of the source code where the associated lifetime is valid.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] In the example above, storing a reference to variable `x` in `r` is valid, as variable `x` has a longer lifetime (`'a`) than variable `r` (`'b`).
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Since the lifetime of the referenced variable (`'b`) is shorter than the lifetime of the variable holding the reference (`'a`), the borrow checker errors, preventing `x` from being used from outside its scope.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Lifetimes can be indicated using explicit *lifetime parameters* on function arguments.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] In the compiler, ownership and lifetimes work together to prevent memory safety issues such as dangling pointers.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] User-defined types are created with the `struct` or `enum` keywords.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The `struct` keyword is used to denote a record type that groups multiple related values.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] `enum`s can take on different variants at runtime, with their capabilities similar to algebraic data types found in functional programming languages.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Both records and enum variants can contain fields with different types.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Alternative names, or aliases, for the same type can be defined with the `type` keyword.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The `impl` keyword can define methods for a user-defined type.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Data and functions are defined separately.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Implementations fulfill a role similar to that of classes within other languages.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust standard library defines and implements many widely used custom data types, including core data structures such as `Vec`, `Option`, and `HashMap`, as well as smart pointer types.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides a way to exclude most of the standard library using the attribute `#![no_std]`, for applications such as embedded devices.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Internally, the standard library is divided into three parts, `core`, `alloc`, and `std`, where `std` and `alloc` are excluded by `#![no_std]`.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Similarly, Rust's result type `Result<T, E>` holds either a successfully computed value (the `Ok` variant) or an error (the `Err` variant).
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Like `Option`, the use of `Result` means that the inner value cannot be used directly; programmers must use a `match` expression, syntactic sugar such as `?` (the "try" operator), or an explicit `unwrap` assertion to access it.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Both `Option` and `Result` are used throughout the standard library and are a fundamental part of Rust's explicit approach to handling errors and missing data.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The `&` and `&mut` reference types are guaranteed to not be null and point to valid memory.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The raw pointer types `*const` and `*mut` opt out of the safety guarantees, thus they may be null or invalid; however, it is impossible to dereference them unless the code is explicitly declared unsafe through the use of an `unsafe` block.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Unlike dereferencing, the creation of raw pointers is allowed inside safe Rust code.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides no implicit type conversion (coercion) between most primitive types.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] But, explicit type conversion (casting) can be performed using the `as` keyword.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports polymorphism through traits, generic functions, and trait objects.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The example above includes a method `is_zero` which provides a default implementation that may be overridden when implementing the trait.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] In the examples above, `Num: Zero` as well as `where Self: PartialEq` are trait bounds that constrain the type to only allow types that implement `Zero` or `PartialEq`.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Within a trait or impl, `Self` refers to the type that the code is implementing.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Generics can be used in functions to allow implementing a behavior for different types without repeating the same code (see bounded parametric polymorphism).
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Generic functions can be written in relation to other generics, without knowing the actual type.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, traits use static dispatch: the compiler monomorphizes the function for each concrete type instance, yielding performance equivalent to type-specific code at the cost of longer compile times and larger binaries.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] When the exact type is not known at compile time, Rust provides trait objects `&dyn Trait` and `Box<dyn Trait>`.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Trait object calls use dynamic dispatch via a lookup table; a trait object is a "fat pointer" carrying both a data pointer and a method table pointer.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] This indirection adds a small runtime cost, but it keeps a single copy of the code and reduces binary size.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Only "object-safe" traits are eligible to be used as trait objects.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] This approach is similar to duck typing, where all data types that implement a given trait can be treated as functionally interchangeable.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] If an element in the list does not implement the `Display` trait, it will cause a compile-time error.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory and other resources are instead managed through the "resource acquisition is initialization" convention, with optional reference counting.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides deterministic management of resources, with very low overhead.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Values are allocated on the stack by default, and all dynamic allocations must be explicit.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The built-in reference types using the `&` symbol do not involve run-time reference counting.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The safety and validity of the underlying pointers are verified at compile time, preventing dangling pointers and other forms of undefined behavior.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's type system separates shared, immutable references of the form `&T` from unique, mutable references of the form `&mut T`.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] A mutable reference can be coerced to an immutable reference, but not vice versa.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's memory safety checks (See #Safety) may be circumvented through the use of `unsafe` blocks.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] This allows programmers to dereference arbitrary raw pointers, call external code, or perform other low-level functionality not allowed by safe Rust.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Some low-level functionality enabled in this way includes volatile memory access, architecture-specific intrinsics, type punning, and inline assembly.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Unsafe code is needed, for example, in the implementation of data structures.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] A frequently cited example is that it is difficult or impossible to implement doubly linked lists in safe Rust.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Programmers using unsafe Rust are considered responsible for upholding Rust's memory and type safety requirements, for example, that no two mutable references exist pointing to the same location.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] If programmers write code that violates these requirements, this results in undefined behavior.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust documentation includes a list of behaviors considered undefined, including accessing dangling or misaligned pointers, or breaking the aliasing rules for references.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Macros allow the generation and transformation of Rust code to reduce repetition.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Macros come in two forms, with *declarative macros* defined through `macro_rules!`, and *procedural macros*, which are defined in separate crates.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] A declarative macro (also called a "macro by example") is a macro, defined using the `macro_rules!` keyword, that uses pattern matching to determine its expansion.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] In this example, the macro named `sum` is defined using the form `macro_rules! sum {` `(...) => { ... } }`.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The first part inside the parentheses of the definition, the macro pattern `( $initial:expr $(, $expr:expr )* $(,)? )` specifies the structure of input it can take.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Here, `$initial:expr` represents the first expression, while `$(, $expr:expr )*` means there can be zero or more additional comma-separated expressions after it.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The trailing `$(,)?` allows the caller to optionally include a final comma without causing an error.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The second part, after the arrow `=>`, describes what code will be generated when the macro is invoked.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] In this case, `$initial $(+ $expr)*` means that the generated code will start with the first expression, followed by a `+` and each of the additional expressions in sequence.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The `*` again means "repeat this pattern zero or more times".
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] This means, when the macro is later called in line 8, as `sum!(1, 2, 3)`, the macro will resolve to `1 + 2 + 3` representing the addition of all of the passed expressions.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Procedural macros are Rust functions that run and modify the compiler's input token stream, before any other components are compiled.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] They are generally more flexible than declarative macros, but are more difficult to maintain due to their complexity.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports the creation of foreign function interfaces (FFI) through the `extern` keyword.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] A function that uses the C calling convention can be written using `extern "C" fn`.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The `#[repr(C)]` attribute enables deterministic memory layouts for `struct`s and `enum`s for use across FFI boundaries.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] External libraries such as `bindgen` and `cxx` can generate Rust bindings for C/C++.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Safety properties guaranteed by Rust include memory safety, type safety, and data race freedom.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] As described above, these guarantees can be circumvented by using the `unsafe` keyword.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory safety includes the absence of dereferences to null, dangling, and misaligned pointers, and the absence of buffer overflows and double free errors.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory leaks may occur as a result of creating reference-counted pointers that point at each other (a reference cycle) or can be deliberately created through calling `Box::leak`.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust ecosystem includes its compiler, its standard library, and additional components for software development.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Component installation is typically managed by `rustup`, a Rust toolchain installer developed by the Rust project.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust compiler, `rustc`, compiles Rust code into binaries.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] First, the compiler parses the source code into an AST.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The compiler backend is then invoked as a subcomponent to apply optimizations and translate the resulting IR into object code.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Finally, a linker is used to combine the object(s) into a single executable image.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] rustc uses LLVM as its compiler backend by default, but it also supports using alternative backends such as GCC and Cranelift.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The intention of those alternative backends is to increase platform coverage of Rust or to improve compilation times.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo is Rust's build system and package manager.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] It downloads, compiles, distributes, and uploads packages—called *crates*—that are maintained in an official registry.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] It also acts as a front-end for Clippy and other Rust components.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, Cargo sources its dependencies from the user-contributed registry *crates.io*, but Git repositories, crates in the local filesystem, and other external sources can also be specified as dependencies.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo supports reproducible builds through two metadata files: Cargo.toml and Cargo.lock.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo.toml declares each package used and their version requirements.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo.lock is generated automatically during dependency resolution and records exact versions of all dependencies, including transitive dependencies.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] It formats whitespace and indentation to produce code in accordance with a common style, unless otherwise specified.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] It can be invoked as a standalone program or from a Rust project through Cargo.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Clippy is Rust's built-in linting tool to improve the correctness, performance, and readability of Rust code.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Following Rust 1.0, new features are developed in *nightly* versions, which are released daily.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] During each six-week release cycle, changes to nightly versions are released to beta, while changes from the previous beta version are released to a new stable version.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Every two or three years, a new "edition" is produced.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Editions are released to allow making limited breaking changes, such as promoting `await` to a keyword to support async/await features.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Crates targeting different editions can interoperate with each other, so a crate can upgrade to a new edition even if its callers or its dependencies still target older editions.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Migration to a new edition can be assisted with automated tooling.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Since it performs no garbage collection, Rust is often faster than other memory-safe languages.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Most of Rust's memory safety guarantees impose no runtime overhead, with the notable exception of array indexing which is checked at runtime by default.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The performance impact of array indexing bounds checks varies, but can be significant in some cases.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Many of Rust's features are so-called *zero-cost abstractions*, meaning they are optimized away at compile time and incur no runtime penalty.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The ownership and borrowing system permits zero-copy implementations for some performance-sensitive tasks, such as parsing.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Static dispatch is used by default to eliminate method calls, except for methods called on dynamic trait objects.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The compiler uses inline expansion to eliminate function calls and statically dispatched method invocations.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Unlike C and C++, Rust allows the compiler to reorder struct and enum elements unless a `#[repr(C)]` representation attribute is applied.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] This allows the compiler to produce more efficient code in some cases.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Performance improvements in LLVM carry over to Rust.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] In web services, OpenDNS, a DNS resolution service owned by Cisco, uses Rust internally.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Amazon Web Services uses Rust in "performance-sensitive components" of services.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2019, AWS open-sourced Firecracker, a virtualization solution primarily written in Rust.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft Azure IoT Edge, a platform used to run Azure services on IoT devices, has components implemented in Rust.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft also uses Rust to run containerized modules with WebAssembly and Kubernetes.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Cloudflare, a company providing content delivery network services, used Rust to build a new web proxy named Pingora for increased performance and efficiency.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The npm package manager used Rust for its production authentication service in 2019.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] In operating systems, the Linux kernel began introducing experimental support for Rust code in Version 6.1 in late 2022, as part of the Rust for Linux project.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The first drivers written in Rust were included in version 6.8.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2025, kernel developers at the Linux Kernel Developers Summit determined the project to be a success, and Rust usage for kernel code will no longer be considered experimental.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The Android developers used Rust in 2021 to rewrite existing components.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft has rewritten parts of Windows in Rust.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The r9 project aims to re-implement Plan 9 from Bell Labs in Rust.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust has also been used in the development of new operating systems such as Redox, a "Unix-like" operating system and microkernel, Theseus, an experimental operating system with modular state management, and most of Fuchsia.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust is used for command-line tools and operating system components such as stratisd, a file system manager and COSMIC, a desktop environment by System76.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] In web development, Deno, a secure runtime for JavaScript and TypeScript, is built on top of V8 using Rust and Tokio.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Other notable adoptions in this space include Ruffle, an open-source SWF emulator, and Polkadot, an open source blockchain and cryptocurrency platform.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Components from the Servo browser engine (funded by Mozilla and Samsung) were incorporated in the Gecko browser engine underlying Firefox.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] In January 2023, Google (Alphabet) announced support for using third party Rust libraries in Chromium.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] In other uses, Discord, an instant messaging software company, rewrote parts of its system in Rust for increased performance in 2020.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] In the same year, Dropbox announced that its file synchronization had been rewritten in Rust.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Facebook (Meta) used Rust to redesign its system that manages source code for internal projects.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] In the 2025 Stack Overflow Developer Survey, 14.8% of respondents had recently done extensive development in Rust.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The survey named Rust the "most admired programming language" annually from 2016 to 2025 (inclusive), as measured by the number of existing developers interested in continuing to work in the language.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2025, 29.2% of developers not currently working in Rust expressed an interest in doing so.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's safety and performance have been investigated in programming languages research.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] In other fields, a journal article published to *Proceedings of the International Astronomical Union* used Rust to simulate multi-planet systems.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] An article published in *Nature* shared stories of bioinformaticians using Rust.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Both articles cited Rust's performance and safety as advantages, and the learning curve as being a primary drawback to Rust adoption.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The 2025 DARPA project TRACTOR aims to automatically translate C to Rust using techniques such as static analysis, dynamic analysis, and large language models.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] According to the *MIT Technology Review*, the Rust community has been seen as "unusually friendly" to newcomers and particularly attracted people from the queer community, partly due to its code of conduct.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] Inclusiveness has been cited as an important factor for some Rust developers.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The official Rust blog collects and publishes demographic data each year.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The **Rust Foundation** is a non-profit membership organization incorporated in United States; it manages the Rust trademark, infrastructure, and assets.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] It was established on February 8, 2021, with five founding corporate members (Amazon Web Services, Huawei, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla).
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The foundation's board was chaired by Shane Miller, with Ashley Williams as interim executive director.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] In late 2021, Rebecca Rumbul became executive director and CEO.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust project is maintained by 8 top-level *teams* as of November 2025: the leadership council, compiler team, dev tools team, infrastructure team, language team, launching pad, library team, and moderation team.
[src:hyper-rust/rust-programming-language] The leadership council oversees the project and is formed by representatives among the other teams.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] A **web API** is an application programming interface (API) for either a web server or a web browser.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] As a web development concept, it can be related to a web application's client side (including any web frameworks being used).
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed **endpoints** to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] A server API (SAPI) is not considered a server-side web API, unless it is publicly accessible by a remote web application.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] A client-side web API is a programmatic interface to extend functionality within a web browser or other HTTP client.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] Originally these were most commonly in the form of native plug-in browser extensions however most newer ones target standardized JavaScript bindings.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] The Mozilla Foundation created their WebAPI specification which is designed to help replace native mobile applications with HTML5 applications.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] Google created their Native Client architecture which is designed to help replace insecure native plug-ins with secure native sandboxed extensions and applications.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] They have also made this portable by employing a modified LLVM AOT compiler.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed *endpoints* to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] The web API is exposed most commonly by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] Endpoints are important aspects of interacting with server-side web APIs, as they specify where resources can be accessed by third-party software.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] Usually the access is via a URI to which HTTP requests are posted, and from which the response is thus expected.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] Web APIs may be public or private, the latter of which requires an *access token*.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] Endpoints need to be static, otherwise the correct functioning of software that interacts with them cannot be guaranteed.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] If the location of a resource changes (and with it the endpoint) then previously written software will break, as the required resource can no longer be found at the same place.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] As API providers still want to update their web APIs, many have introduced a versioning system in the URI that points to an endpoint.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] Web 2.0 Web APIs often use machine-based interactions such as REST and SOAP.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] RESTful web APIs use HTTP methods to access resources via URL-encoded parameters, and use JSON or XML to transmit data.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] By contrast, SOAP protocols are standardized by the W3C and mandate the use of XML as the payload format, typically over HTTP.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] Furthermore, SOAP-based Web APIs use XML validation to ensure structural message integrity, by leveraging the XML schemas provisioned with WSDL documents.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] A WSDL document accurately defines the XML messages and transport bindings of a Web service.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] Server-side web APIs are interfaces for the outside world to interact with the business logic.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] For many companies this internal business logic and the intellectual property associated with it are what distinguishes them from other companies, and potentially what gives them a competitive edge.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] They do not want this information to be exposed.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] However, in order to provide a web API of high quality, there *needs* to be a sufficient level of documentation.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] One API provider that not only provides documentation, but also links to it in its error messages is Twilio.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] However, there are now directories of popular documented server-side web APIs.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] The number of available web APIs has grown consistently over the past years, as businesses realize the growth opportunities associated with running an open platform, that any developer can interact with.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] ProgrammableWeb tracks over 24000 Web APIs that were available in 2022, up from 105 in 2005.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] There are few major software applications/services that do not offer some form of web API.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] One of the most common forms of interacting with these web APIs is via embedding external resources, such as tweets, Facebook comments, YouTube videos, etc.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] In fact there are very successful companies, such as Disqus, whose main service is to provide embeddable tools, such as a feature-rich comment system.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] Any website of the TOP 100 Alexa Internet ranked websites uses APIs and/or provides its own APIs, which is a very distinct indicator for the prodigious scale and impact of web APIs as a whole.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] As the number of available web APIs has grown, open source tools have been developed to provide more sophisticated search and discovery.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] APIs.json provides a machine-readable description of an API and its operations, and the related project APIs.io offers a searchable public listing of APIs based on the APIs.json metadata format.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] Many companies and organizations rely heavily on their Web API infrastructure to serve their core business clients.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] In 2014 Netflix received around 5 billion API requests, most of them within their private API.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] Many governments collect a lot of data, and some governments are now opening up access to this data.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] The interfaces through which this data is typically made accessible are web APIs.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] Web APIs allow for data, such as "budget, public works, crime, legal, and other agency data" to be accessed by any developer in a convenient manner.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] An example of a popular web API is the Astronomy Picture of the Day API operated by the American space agency NASA.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] It is a server-side API used to retrieve photographs of space or other images of interest to astronomers, and metadata about the images.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] The documentation states that this endpoint accepts GET requests.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] It requires one piece of information from the user, an API key, and accepts several other optional pieces of information.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] Such pieces of information are known as *parameters*.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] The parameters for this API are written in a format known as a query string, which is separated by a question mark character (`?`) from the endpoint.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] An ampersand (`&`) separates the parameters in the query string from each other.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] Together, the endpoint and the query string form a URL that determines how the API will respond.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] This URL is also known as a *query* or an *API call*.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] In the below example, two parameters are transmitted (or *passed*) to the API via the query string.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] The first is the required API key and the second is an optional parameter — the date of the photograph requested.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] Visiting the above URL in a web browser will initiate a GET request, calling the API and showing the user a result, known as a *return value* or as a *return*.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] This API returns JSON, a type of data format intended to be understood by computers, but which is somewhat easy for a human to read as well.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] The above API return has been reformatted so that names of JSON data items, known as *keys*, appear at the start of each line.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] Although this API can be called by an end user with a web browser (as in this example) it is intended to be called automatically by software or by computer programmers while writing software.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] JSON is intended to be parsed by a computer program, which would extract the URL of the photograph and the other metadata.
[src:hyper-rust/web-api] The resulting photo could be embedded in a website, automatically sent via text message, or used for any other purpose envisioned by a software developer.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] A **web server** is computer software that accepts requests via HTTP (the network protocol created to distribute web content) or its secure variant HTTPS.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] A user agent, commonly a web browser or web crawler, initiates communication by making a request for a web page or other resource using HTTP, and the server responds with the content of that resource or an error message.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] A web server can also accept and store resources sent from the user agent if configured to do so.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] The hardware used to run a web server can vary according to the volume of requests that it needs to handle.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] At the low end of the range are embedded systems, such as a router that runs a small web server as its configuration interface.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] A high-traffic Internet website might handle requests with hundreds of servers that run on racks of high-speed computers.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] A resource sent from a web server can be a pre-existing file (static content) available to the web server, or it can be generated at the time of the request (dynamic content) by another program that communicates with the server software.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] The former usually can be served faster and can be more easily cached for repeated requests, while the latter supports a broader range of applications.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Technologies such as REST and SOAP, which use HTTP as a basis for general computer-to-computer communication, as well as support for WebDAV extensions, have extended the application of web servers well beyond their original purpose of serving human-readable pages.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] In March 1989, Sir Tim Berners-Lee proposed a new project to his employer CERN, with the goal of easing the exchange of information between scientists by using a hypertext system.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] The proposal titled *"HyperText and CERN"*, asked for comments and it was read by several people.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] In October 1990 the proposal was reformulated and enriched (having as co-author Robert Cailliau), and finally, it was approved.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Those early browsers retrieved web pages written in a simple early form of HTML from web servers using a new basic communication protocol that was named HTTP 0.9.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] In August 1991 Tim Berners-Lee announced the *birth of WWW technology* and encouraged scientists to adopt and develop it.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Soon after, those programs, along with their source code, were made available to people interested in their usage.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Although the source code was not formally licensed or placed in the public domain, CERN informally allowed users and developers to experiment and further develop on top of them.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Berners-Lee started promoting the adoption and the usage of those programs along with their porting to other operating systems.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] In December 1991, the **first web server outside Europe** was installed at SLAC (U.S.A.).
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] This was a very important event because it started trans-continental web communications between web browsers and web servers.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] In 1991–1993, CERN web server program continued to be actively developed by the www group, meanwhile, thanks to the availability of its source code and the public specifications of the HTTP protocol, many other implementations of web servers started to be developed.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] In April 1993, CERN issued a public official statement stating that the three components of Web software (the basic line-mode client, the web server and the library of common code), along with their source code, were put in the public domain.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] This statement freed web server developers from any possible legal issue about the development of *derivative work* based on that source code (a threat that in practice never existed).
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] At the beginning of 1994, the most notable among new web servers was NCSA httpd which ran on a variety of Unix-based OSs and could serve *dynamically generated content* by implementing the `POST` HTTP method and the CGI to communicate with external programs.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] These capabilities, along with the multimedia features of NCSA's Mosaic browser (also able to manage HTML FORMs in order to send data to a web server) highlighted the potential of web technology for publishing and distributed computing applications.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] At the beginning of 1995 those patches were all applied to the last release of NCSA source code and, after several tests, the Apache HTTP server project was started.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] At the end of 1994, a new commercial web server, named Netsite, was released with specific features.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] It was the first one of many other similar products that were developed first by Netscape, then also by Sun Microsystems, and finally by Oracle Corporation.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] In mid-1995, the first version of IIS was released by Microsoft for Windows NT OS.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] This marked the entry, in the field of World Wide Web technologies, of a commercial developer and vendor that has played and still is playing a key role on both sides (client and server) of the web.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] In the second half of 1995, CERN and NCSA web servers started to decline (in global percentage usage) because of the widespread adoption of new web servers which had a much faster development cycle along with more features, more fixes applied, and more performances than the previous ones.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] At the end of 1996, there were already over fifty known, different web-server-software programs that were available to everybody who wanted to own an Internet domain name or to host websites.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Many of them lived only shortly and were replaced by other web servers.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] The publication of RFCs about protocol versions HTTP/1.0 (1996) and HTTP/1.1 (1997, 1999), forced most web servers to comply (not always completely) with those standards.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] The use of TCP/IP persistent connections (HTTP/1.1) required web servers both to increase the maximum number of concurrent connections allowed and to improve their level of scalability.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Between 1996 and 1999, Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's IIS emerged among the leading commercial options whereas among the freely available and open-source programs Apache HTTP Server held the lead as the preferred server (because of its reliability and its many features).
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] In those years there was also another commercial web server called Zeus (*now discontinued*) that was known as one of the fastest and most scalable web servers available on market, at least till the first decade of 2000s, despite its low percentage of usage.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Apache resulted in the most used web server from mid-1996 to the end of 2015 when, after a few years of decline, it was surpassed initially by IIS and then by Nginx.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Afterward IIS dropped to much lower percentages of usage than Apache (see also market share).
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] From 2005–2006, Apache started to improve its speed and its scalability level by introducing new performance features (e.g., event MPM and new content cache).
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] A few years after 2000 started, not only other commercial and highly competitive web servers (e.g., LiteSpeed) but also many other open-source programs such as Hiawatha, Cherokee HTTP server, Lighttpd, Nginx and other derived and related products also available with commercial support emerged.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Within a year, these changes, on average, nearly tripled the maximum number of persistent connections that web servers had to manage.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] In 2015, RFCs published new protocol version [HTTP/2], and as the implementation of new specifications was not trivial at all, a **dilemma arose among developers of less popular web servers** (e.g., with a percentage of usage lower than 1% ..
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] 2%), about adding or not adding support for that new protocol version.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] In 2020–2021 the HTTP/2 dynamics about its implementation (by top web servers and popular web browsers) were partly replicated after the publication of advanced drafts of future RFC about HTTP/3 protocol.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] The following technical overview should be considered only as an attempt to give a few very *limited examples* about *some* features that may be implemented in a web server and *some* of the tasks that it may perform in order to have a sufficiently wide scenario about the topic.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] A **web server program** plays the role of a server in a client–server model by implementing one or more versions of HTTP protocol, often including the HTTPS secure variant and other features and extensions that are considered useful for its planned usage.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Although web server programs differ in how they are implemented, most of them offer the following common features.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] These are **basic features** that most web servers usually have.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] A few other more **advanced** and popular **features** (*only a very short selection*) are the following ones.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Once an HTTP request message has been decoded and verified, its values can be used to determine whether that request can be satisfied or not.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] This requires many other steps, including **security checks**.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] The term *URL normalization* refers to the process of modifying and standardizing a URL in a consistent manner.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] There are several types of normalization that may be performed, including the conversion of the scheme and host to lowercase.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Among the most important normalizations are the removal of "." and ".." path segments and adding trailing slashes to a non-empty path component.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] One or more configuration files of web server may specify the mapping of parts of **URL path** (e.g., initial parts of file path, filename extension and other path components) to a specific URL handler (file, directory, external program or internal module).
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Web server programs are able to translate an URL path (all or part of it), that refers to a physical file system path, to an absolute path under the target website's root directory.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Website's root directory may be specified by a configuration file or by some internal rule of the web server by using the name of the website which is the host part of the URL found in HTTP client request.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] The web server appends the path found in requested URL (HTTP request message) and appends it to the path of the (Host) website root directory.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] On an Apache server, this is commonly `/home/www/website` (on Unix machines, usually it is: `/var/www/website`).
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] See the following examples of how it may result.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] The web server then reads the file, if it exists, and sends a response to the client's web browser.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] The response will describe the content of the file and contain the file itself or an error message will return saying that the file does not exist or its access is forbidden.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] The response will describe the content of the directory (list of contained subdirectories and files) or an error message will return saying that the directory does not exist or its access is forbidden.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] For a *dynamic request* the URL path specified by the client should refer to an existing external program (usually an executable file with a CGI) used by the web server to generate dynamic content.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] The web server executes that program, passing in the path-info and the query string `action=view&orderby=thread&date=2021-10-15` so that the program has the info it needs to run.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] (In this case, it will return an HTML document containing a view of forum entries ordered by thread from October 15, 2021).
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] In addition to this, the web server reads data sent from the external program and resends that data to the client that made the request.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Once a request has been read, interpreted, and verified, it has to be managed depending on its method, its URL, and its parameters, which may include values of HTTP headers.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] That kind of content is called *static* because usually it is not changed by the web server when it is sent to clients and because it remains the same until it is modified (file modification) by some program.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Response of static file content can be sped up by a **file cache**.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Most used names for static index files are: `index.html`, `index.htm` and `Default.htm`.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] If a web server program receives a client request message with an URL whose path matches the file name of an existing *file* and that file is accessible by web server program and its attributes match internal rules of web server program, then web server program can send that file to client.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Usually, for security reasons, most web server programs are pre-configured to serve only regular files or to avoid to use *special file types* like device files, along with symbolic links or hard links to them.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] The aim is to avoid undesirable side effects when serving static web resources.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] If a web server program is capable of **serving dynamic content** and it has been configured to do so, then it is able to communicate with the proper internal module or external program (associated with the requested URL path) in order to pass to it the parameters of the client request.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] After that, the web server program reads from it its data response (that it has generated, often on the fly) and then it resends it to the client program who made the request.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] In order to be able to communicate with its internal modules or external programs, a web server program must have implemented one or more of the many available **gateway interfaces** (see also Web Server Gateway Interfaces used for dynamic content).
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] The three **standard** and historical **gateway interfaces** are the following ones.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] An external CGI program is run by web server program for each dynamic request, then web server program reads from it the generated data response and then resends it to client.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] An external FastCGI program (it usually is a process) is started once by web server program or by some other program or process and then it waits for a network connection which is established permanently by web server; through that connection are sent the request parameters and read data responses.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] A web server program may be capable to manage the dynamic generation (on the fly) of a **directory index list** of files and sub-directories.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] If it cannot be generated an error is returned.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Usage of dynamically generated *directory listings* is usually avoided or limited to a few selected directories of a website because that generation takes much more OS resources than sending a static index page.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] The main usage of *directory listings* is to allow the download of files (usually when their names, sizes, modification date-times or file attributes may change randomly and frequently) *as they are, without requiring to provide further information to requesting user*.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] In practice whenever there is content that may vary, depending on one or more parameters contained in client request or in configuration settings, then, usually, it is generated dynamically.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Web server programs are able to send response messages as replies to client request messages.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] An error response message may be sent because a request message could not be successfully read or decoded or analyzed or executed.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] NOTE: the following sections are reported only as examples to help to understand what a web server, more or less, does; these sections are by any means neither exhaustive nor complete.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] When an error response or message is received by a client browser, then if it is related to the main user request (e.g., an URL of a web resource such as a web page) then usually that error message is shown in some browser window or message.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Example 1: a URL path points to a **directory** name but it does not have a final slash '/' so web server sends a redirect to client in order to instruct it to redo the request with the fixed path name.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Example 2: a whole set of documents has been **moved inside website** in order to reorganize their file system paths.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Example 3: a whole set of documents has been **moved to a new website** and now it is mandatory to use secure HTTPS connections to access them.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Above examples are only a few of the possible kind of redirections.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] A web server program is able to reply to a valid client request message with a successful message, optionally containing requested **web resource data**.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] If web resource data is sent back to client, then it can be **static content** or **dynamic content** depending on how it has been retrieved (from a file or from the output of some program or module).
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] In order to speed up web server responses by lowering average HTTP response times and hardware resources used, many popular web servers implement one or more content caches, each one specialized in a content category.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] In practice, nowadays, many web server programs include their own *userland* **file cache**, tailored for a web server usage and using their specific implementation and parameters.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] The wide spread adoption of RAID and fast solid-state drives (storage hardware with very high I/O speed) has slightly reduced but of course not eliminated the advantage of having a file cache incorporated in a web server.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Dynamic content, output by an internal module or an external program, may not always change very frequently (given a unique URL with keys or parameters) and so, maybe for a while (e.g., from one second to several hours or more), the resulting output can be cached in RAM or even on a fast disk.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Anyway, in most cases those kind of caches are implemented by external servers (e.g., reverse proxy) or by storing dynamic data output in separate computers, managed by specific applications (e.g., memcached), in order to not compete for hardware resources (CPU, RAM, disks) with web servers.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] A web server software can be either incorporated into the OS and executed in kernel space, or it can be executed in user space (like other regular applications).
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Web servers that run in user-mode have to ask the system for permission to use more memory or more CPU resources.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Not only do these requests to the kernel take time, but they might not always be satisfied because the system reserves resources for its own usage and has the responsibility to share hardware resources with all the other running applications.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Executing in user mode can also mean using more buffer or data copies (between user-space and kernel-space) which can lead to a decrease in the performance of a user-mode web server.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Nowadays almost all web server software is executed in user mode (because many of the aforementioned small disadvantages have been overcome by faster hardware, new OS versions, much faster OS system calls and new optimized web server software).
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] See also comparison of web server software to discover which of them run in kernel mode or in user mode (also referred as kernel space or user space).
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] In other words, a **web server should always be very responsive**, even under high load of web traffic, in order to keep **total user's wait** (sum of browser time + network time + **web server response time**) for a response **as low as possible**.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Among the operating conditions, the **number** (1 ..
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] *n*) of **concurrent client connections** used during a test is an important parameter because it allows to correlate the **concurrency level** supported by web server with results of the tested performance metrics.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] ... used to implement a web server program, **can bias a lot the performances** and in particular the **scalability level** that can be achieved under **heavy load** or when using high end hardware (many CPUs, disks and lots of RAM).
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] In practice some web server software models may require more OS resources (specially more CPUs and more RAM) than others to be able to work well and so to achieve target performances.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p01] Performances of a web server are typically benchmarked by using one or more of the available automated load testing tools.
[src:hyper-rust/web-server-p02] When a web server is near to or over its load limits, it gets **overloaded** and so it may become **unresponsive**.
